Sure, to create an HTML form that works with the Java Servlet code provided earlier, you can use the following HTML code. This form will send a POST request to the server when the submit button is clicked, which will be handled by the `StudentInfoServlet`:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Student Information Form</title>
</head>
<body>

<h1>Student Information Form</h1>

<form action="StudentInfoServlet" method="post">
    <label for="rollNumber">Roll Number:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="rollNumber" name="rollNumber"><br><br>

    <label for="studentName">Student Name:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="studentName" name="studentName"><br><br>

    <label for="address">Student Address:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="address" name="address"><br><br>

    <label for="phone">Phone:</label><br>
    <input type="text" id="phone" name="phone"><br><br>

    <label for="marks">Total Marks:</label><br>
    <input type="number" id="marks" name="marks"><br><br>

    <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form> 

</body>
</html>
```

Make sure that your web server is running and that the `StudentInfoServlet` is correctly mapped in your web application's deployment descriptor (`web.xml`) or through annotations, so that the form knows where to send the data upon submission. If you have any more questions or need further assistance, feel free to ask!

